83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
House Bill 4155
Sponsored by Representative ELMER; Representatives BOICE, BUNCH, EDWARDS, HELFRICH, LEVY B, LEWIS,
MANNIX, MCINTIRE, OSBORNE, SCHARF, SKARLATOS, YUNKER (Presession filed.)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure as introduced. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability
standards.
Digest: The Act tells some insurers, OEBB and PEBB to cover care for some fertility treat-
ments. The Act tells OHA and DCBS to study access to reproductive treatments and report back to
the committee on health. The Act makes it an emergency. (Flesch Readability Score: 65.0).
Requires certain health insurers, the Oregon Educators Benefit Board and the Public Employees’
Benefit Board to cover fertility services and treatments.
Directs the Oregon Health Authority and the Department of Consumer and Business Services
to study access to fertility and reproductive endocrinology services and report findings to the in-
terim committees of the Legislative Assembly related to health.
Declares an emergency, effective on passage.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to infertility; creating new provisions; amending ORS 243.144, 243.877 and 743B.005; and
3 declaring an emergency.
4 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
5 SECTION 1. Section 2 of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of the Insurance Code.
6 SECTION 2. (1) As used in this section, “infertility” means:
7 (a) A disease, condition or status that results in a failure to establish a pregnancy or to
8 carry a pregnancy to a live birth after regular, unprotected sexual intercourse for:
9 (A) Twelve months for a woman under the age of 35; or
10 (B) Six months for a woman 35 years of age or older; or
11 (b) An individual’s inability, without medical intervention, to reproduce either as a single
12 person or with the person’s partner.
13 (2) Health benefit plans offered in this state to large or small employers and individual
14 health benefit plans offered in this state shall reimburse the cost of:
15 (a) Procedures and medications to address infertility recommended by a licensed treating
16 practitioner that are:
17 (A) Based on the practitioner’s physical findings and diagnostic testing and an
18 individual’s medical history, sexual history, reproductive history and age; and
19 (B) Consistent with established, published or approved medical practices or professional
20 guidelines from the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists or the American
21 Society for Reproductive Medicine, or a successor organization.
22 (b) Procedures recommended by a licensed treating practitioner, including but not limited
23 to the storage of reproductive specimens for the period of time deemed medically necessary
24 by the practitioner, that are:
25 (A) Based on the practitioner’s physical findings and diagnostic testing and an
26 individual’s medical history, sexual history, reproductive history and age; and
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 299

HB 4155
1 (B) Consistent with established medical practices or professional guidelines published by
2 the American Society for Reproductive Medicine or the American Society of Clinical
3 Oncology, or a successor organization, for an individual who is at risk of infertility due to:
4 (i) A medical condition; or
5 (ii) An expected medication therapy, surgery, radiation, chemotherapy or other medical
6 treatment that is recognized by medical professionals to cause a risk of infertility.
7 (3) The coverage for diagnosis and treatment related to infertility required by subsection
8 (2) of this section:
9 (a) Includes a minimum of three completed oocyte retrievals with unlimited embryo
10 transfers in accordance with guidelines of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine,
11 or a successor organization, using single embryo transfer if recommended by a licensed
12 treating practitioner and medically effective.
13 (b) Must be provided to all beneficiaries under the health benefit plan policy or certif-
14 icate, including a covered spouse and covered dependents other than spouses, to the same
15 extent as other pregnancy-related benefits under the plan.
16 (4) The health benefit plan may not impose exclusions, limitations or other restrictions
17 on coverage of:
18 (a) Medications for the treatment of infertility described in subsection (2) of this section
19 that are not imposed on other prescription benefits under the plan.
20 (b) Procedures described in subsections (2) and (3) of this section:
21 (A) Based on an enrollee’s participation in fertility services provided by or to a third
22 party.
23 (B) That do not apply to other covered procedures under the plan.
24 (5) Subsection (4) of this section does not permit a health benefit plan to require step
25 therapy for services described in subsections (2) and (3) of this section that are determined
26 by a treating practitioner to be medically necessary.
27 (6) This section is exempt from ORS 743A.001.
28 SECTION 3. (1) The Oregon Health Authority, in collaboration with the Department of
29 Consumer and Business Services, shall study access to fertility and reproductive
30 endocrinology services by residents of this state, including:
31 (a) Availability and utilization of fertility and reproductive endocrinology services in the
32 commercial health insurance markets, self-insured health plans and the state medical as-
33 sistance program;
34 (b) Financial and access barriers to obtaining fertility and reproductive endocrinology
35 services including assisted reproductive technology; and
36 (c) Inequities in access to fertility and reproductive endocrinology services based on race,
37 ethnicity, gender identity, sexual orientation, income, marital status, immigration status and
38 disability.
39 (2) No later than September 15, 2027, the authority shall report to the interim commit-
40 tees of the Legislative Assembly related to health, in the manner provided in ORS 192.245,
41 the findings of the study described in subsection (1) of this section and recommendations for:
42 (a) Reducing financial and access barriers to fertility and reproductive endocrinology
43 services for residents of this state;
44 (b) Strategies to promote equal access to fertility and reproductive endocrinology ser-
45 vices, including protections against discrimination in the provision of fertility and reproduc-
[2]

